[Event "Berlin — the Evergreen Game"]
[Site "Berlin"]
[Date "1852.??.??"]
[White "Adolf Anderssen"]
[Black "Jean Dufresne"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Blurb "Wilhelm Steinitz called it 'evergreen in the laurel crown' of Anderssen. Another Evans Gambit, another storm of sacrifices — capped by one of the prettiest queen offers on record."]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5
4. b4 {The Evans Gambit: a pawn thrown in to seize tempo and the centre.} Bxb4
5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 exd4 7. O-O d3 {Black hands the pawn back to slow White's build-up.}
8. Qb3 Qf6 9. e5 Qg6 10. Re1 Nge7 11. Ba3 {The bishop stops Black from castling to safety.} b5
12. Qxb5 Rb8 13. Qa4 Bb6 14. Nbd2 Bb7 15. Ne4 Qf5 16. Bxd3 Qh5
17. Nf6+ {A shot to rip open the g-file.} gxf6 18. exf6 Rg8 {Both kings are in the open now — it is a straight race to mate.}
19. Rad1 {The move that made the game evergreen: Anderssen ignores his own hanging bishop and brings the last piece in.} Qxf3
20. Rxe7+ {The combination breaks. Everything is sacrificed with a purpose.} Nxe7
21. Qxd7+ {A queen sacrifice to strip the king bare.} Kxd7
22. Bf5+ {The double-check idea hauls the king into a net it can't escape.} Ke8
23. Bd7+ Kf8 24. Bxe7# {Checkmate. A finish worth memorising just for its beauty.}
